The coefficient of $x^k$ in the expansion of $(x + 3)^{50}$ can be found using the binomial theorem.
Using the multiplication theorem, we have:
\begin{align*}
(x + 3)^{50} &\equiv \sum_{i = 0}^{50}\binom{50}{i}x^{i}3^{50 - i}.\end{align*}
From this, and equating $i$ to $k$, we have:
\begin{align*}
(x + 3)^{50} &\equiv \binom{50}{k}x^{k}3^{50 - k}\end{align*}
From this, we know that the coefficient of $x^k$ is:
\begin{align*}\binom{50}{k}3^{50 - k}\end{align*}
Now, we know that these coefficients will be maximized when $3^{50 - k}$ is maximized, which occurs when $3^{50 - k}$ = largest, or equivalently when:
\begin{align*}k = 1.\end{align*}
So, the coefficient of $x^k$ is maximized when $k = 1$.
